      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Now I can see the schema. \n\nLooking at the `assetCard` type, I can see the `image` field has a sub-field called `media` which is `type: \"globalDocumentReference\"` and is `hidden: true`. That's the nested media field. But the issue was described as having a \"duplicate `media` field\". Let me look more carefully...\n\nActually, the problem description was:\n> Schema corruption in Sanity — `assetCard` type has a duplicate `media` field from a double-deployment. Every `deploy_schema` call fails until you run one local CLI command.\n\nLooking at the schema, I see the `image` field in `assetCard` has a nested `media` field within it (in the `fields` array of the image type). But I don't see a duplicate top-level `media` field. Maybe the corruption is at the schema level (the `$.schemas.default` document itself has duplicate entries).\n\nWait, the issue could be that the schema document was deployed twice and there might be a conflict in the schema document. Let me look more carefully at the raw JSON.\n\nActually, since we need to delete the `media` duplicate from `assetCard`, the approach the user mentioned was:\n```\nsanity schema delete --project wdcy2hfs --dataset production --workspace default\n```\n\nBut the actual CLI command needs schema IDs. Let me think about this differently. The schema is stored in a single document `_.schemas.default`. To fix it, we might need to:\n1. Delete the corrupt schema document\n2. Then redeploy the correct schema via the Sanity MCP/API\n\nOr we could directly update the schema document. But actually, looking at the schema more carefully, the `assetCard` image field has:\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"image\",\n  \"type\": \"image\",\n  \"fields\": [{\n    \"name\": \"media\",\n    \"type\": \"globalDocumentReference\",\n    ...\n    \"hidden\": true\n  }],\n  \"title\": \"Image\",\n  \"options\": {\"hotspot\": true}\n}\n```\n\nAnd then there might also be a top-level `media` field that was added by the duplicate deployment. But I don't see it in the current schema output. Let me look again more carefully...\n\nHmm, I don't actually see a duplicate in the current schema. Maybe the issue was already partially fixed or the schema was deployed differently. Let me try the simplest approach: delete the `assetCard` schema and then we can redeploy.\n\nThe command should be:\n```\nsanity schema delete --ids assetCard -p wdcy2hfs -d production\n```\n\nLet me try that.",
